54.review_text: My elderly mom has used this phone for the past six or eight months or so. Before that she had the Samsung Knack which is virtually the identical phone. Both phones work well and are fairly well suited for the person who wants a no-frills, basic, easy-to-use phone. For the most part, the display is easy to see. The ability to adjust font size is very helpful, however, the largest size isn't quiet large enough for an elderly woman with limited sight. The buttons are easy to use. Occasionally the menu requires the user to hit a button twice for confirmation which can be kind of confusing. For example, in order to listen to a voice mail message, you need to select the message, then select it AGAIN to "listen." There are two glaring problems with the Samsung Haven, both of which were carried over from the Knack. First of all, the side-mount buttons are on the main body of the phone rather than on the flip-up display. It's virtually impossible to handle this phone without pressing one of the side buttons by mistake. The only way to keep from pressing a side-mount button by mistake is to hold the phone by the display, and I don't know of ANYONE who holds their flip-phone that way! Due to this poor design, on several occasions my mom has inadvertently lowered and/or turned off the volume to the point that she missed important phone calls. It's very disconcerting to check in on my mom and get no answer, which leads me to think something is wrong, when in fact, the ringer was just turned off. I just hope if she ever CAN'T answer her phone because she's hurt or something, that I don't shrug it off assuming the ringer is turned off again. The other big problem is the fact that the battery just doesn't last. The only reason she got rid of her Samsung Knack is because the battery died and it would have cost more to get a new battery than to get a new phone! The same goes for her Samsung Haven. She's had her Samsung Haven for not quite a year, and here I am looking for a new phone for her again because her battery is about to die! Now that I'm in the market to replace her Samsung Haven, I'd really like to find a better, more well-designed phone for my mom. Unfortunately, having to learn how to use a new phone would be so difficult for her, that she'd much rather overlook the problems and have me buy another Samsung Haven, than find a phone better suited to her needs.

69.review_text: I recently upgraded to this phone from my galaxy S for the new android OS and 4g speeds. However I did not realize all that I would be giving up with the "upgrade". The Good -Excellent phone call clarity -Perfect size for one handed use -Excellent display (wouldn't call it bright however) -Fast The Bad -Swype was perfect in the Galaxy S, I didn't even have to look at my phone half the time. With the Stellar I have to manually type words in because it will auto correct to ridiculous suggestions. I have tried adjusting the sensitivity but nothing seems to work. Frustrating that it worked so well on another phone. -4gb internal storage. I know it sounds like plenty especially with an expansion slot, but this phone does not support (or I can't figure out how to get it to) moving Apps to the external SD card. Keep in mind that by the time Samsung and Verizon put all their software on the phone internal storage is less than 1 gb. For anyone who likes to listen to internet radio, use maps, play games on their phone you will be constantly filling up the internal memory. Conclusion - Overall good phone (great for the price) and a solid basic smartphone. I would recommend to anyone looking for a basic smart phone with all the bare-bones essentials.

90.review_text: I am no stranger to Mobile devices. I have went through the Iphone 4s, Galaxy S3, Iphone 5, Galaxy note II and now upon the Galaxy S4. I will say the S4 is not my FAVORITE out of all my phones, and let me explain why. Going from the Galaxy S3 to the Note II was a big difference. In the terms of having multiple windows open at a time, picture quality was outstanding, and the size was much different. Now going from the Note II to the S 4, feels like I actually downgraded. Smaller and slimmer was nice, but overall there was nothing really new. Yes, it has smart auto stay and auto scroll. Honestly, the scroll has major flaws, and does not accurately read your eyes. The auto stay, for pausing the video when you look away is a nice idea, however, it still pauses even when you are looking at the screen. Overall, not very impressed with the Galaxy S4, just hope it doesn't turn in how apple updates their products. By that, adding a 5 and updating to 4g, which was long overdue. Come on samsung, you're better than this, hopping for an update soon, to provide additional feature. Fingers crossed to get 4.3 in the near future. ( hint ) and maybe I can get my hands onto the Galaxy Note III here in the future. Will say, if you want more for your money, the Note II or the new Note III will be the way to go. :)

91.review_text: My kids were always bugging me to upgrade from my flip phone, but I didn't see the need to spend money on technology I would never use. I bought the S4 days before my vacation and must say that it was easy to learn, great to stay connected to family and friends while I was away, and the GPS and Google Maps were invaluable! I should have done this sooner. I do find this a little large to carry in pants pockets and my only serious "con" is that the speaker is on the back of the phone, which just doesn't make sense when you are using the front!
91.review_title: Amazing equipment for a 1st time smartphone user

95.review_text: This is the best phone I have owned hands down. It is very fast & full of features with a large display. Every program that I have installed has run flawlessly with no problem whatsoever. The only negative thing about this phone that I really dislike is the expandable sd memory. It's expandable to 64gb sd which is useless, because the phone only reads programs from internal memory which is 16gb. I installed two games and now, have less than 5gb left so I have to play these games, uninstall them, and put new games on. I have a 32gb sd card but you don't have the option of moving apps to the sd card which doesn't make any sense. Keep in mind that I have had this phone only a couple months, so I don't have a lot of apps on the phone, just a couple games and apps. The less than 5gb is a lot of programs that come on the phone, so that limits the programs that I can install without having the option to move to the sd card.

105.review_text: First time coming to Samsung Phone from my Other brand Android Phone. First of with all the Pros, Its Light weight, Colorful, Fast with all great features for a next gen smartphone. Of all Phones i had this one has best Voice Quality. Display is one of great feature with Brighter colors. Great Plus are replaceable Battery and add Micro SD card. Though it has all advance features, the quality of material is looks cheap especially the back cover of Phone. Also they advertise it as Gorilla Glass 2 but it gets crack easily and the display has finger prints on usage. Camera is 8MP but the picture quality is great in Sun light still images only. No image stabilization and not good at medium or low light and still not a replacement for normal point and shoot camera. It has huge battery capacity so i would expect at least 2 days between charges but have to charge everyday. If they remove lots of bloatwares, it would get expected Battery life. Build in HDMI would have been great instead of MHL which we need to buy it.

109.review_text: Overall I like this smartphone. Storage capacity is good and you can add a micro sd card for additional storage although you have to take the back cover off and remove the battery to install it. Talk time and overall battery life is poor. Barely gets me through an 8 hour day if I talk for 60 minutes on the phone. Needs a better over the air sync and backup method that is efficient to work with syncing with common desktop business software for contacts, notes and tasks. The one provided is slow and connecting via the usb is inconsistant and the wifi connection expects that the pc has a wifi on it so if you have a hardwired desktop pc it does not provide for a router wifi connection between phone and pc.

117.review_text: The phone has all the features that I wanted and it will get the ICS update. It works on T-Mobile's HSPA+ 42Mbps network (8Mb down, 3Mb up in San Diego). I don't need or want LTE, so that is why I went with T-Mobile. I didn't get the Galaxy S III because frankly, it's too big. While it is state of the art, it wouldn't fit in my pockets and hands. I wanted a 4" device and this the Blaze was perfect. Now the bad. - There is no "stay awake" feature when connected to power/usb. I'm not sure why Samsung decided to remove that feature. I had to download an app, that doesn't work great. - I've had it for 1 week, and the phone did crash once. - Just now, I lost network registration while trying to make a call. I had to put it in/out Airplane mode to re-register on the network.

120.review_text: THE BATTERY LASTS ALL DAY LONG with full usage!!! Incredible phone. The S-Pen is genius. I love being able to take notes, write on pictures and so much more. Sure, it's a little big in your pocket, but you get used to it real fast. I don't wear tight pants, but I do wear fitted--the phone fits wonderfully. WHY FOUR STARS? The star came off because of a issue that I've been having with the phone. When I record video, the audio isn't guaranteed. I'm not sure if it's a software problem or if it's where the mic is located--because my fingers seem to always be there. So that design in flawed is my opinion. Everything else has been really incredible. I'm definitely going to be sticking with this phone model for the next few releases--unless Samsung reveal something better but same size! :)

123.review_text: This phone is simply, the best phone i've ever had. It is fantastic. The big screen, customization, features are just what a phone needs to be amazing. The camera takes flawless pictures, and even more flawless videos. I would recommend this phone to anyone. It has something for everyone. The only thing that has me disappointed about the phone -and the reason I gave it an overall rating of 4, as well as in performance-, it's that it overheats all of the sudden -it may be for the NFC and S Beam capability it has-, and the battery doesn't last too long on a regular use, so make sure to keep your charger near -let's wait until they release the extended battery this spring-. This isn't very important, but the display brightness could improve a lot when it comes to using it on sunlight, since you can't barely see anything. I really love the design of the phone, yet, I think it can get much much better than this. Counting out the flaws it has. This has been the best phone i've ever got to hold.

126.review_text: I've been a fan of Samsung for years, had the gs2, 3, galaxy 7 from tmobile, note 10.1 and have never been disappointed. this phone is a powerhouse, it's great at multitasking and the screen is big enough to multitask efficiently. the display is nothing less than I expected for the money I spent and the s-pen works very well, I wasn't sure what to expect as compared to my note 10.1. the only drawback is this thing is HUGE. Samsung did a great job of keeping the bezel slim to maximize the screen size without making it too bulky, but I have to wear cargo pants to fit it in a pocket. one feature I really like is the one handed operation. it will let you move the keyboard to one side or the other so you can easily type (or swipe) with your thumb, it's about a 2/3 size keyboard, otherwise there is no way I could text with one hand. overall i'm very impressed with the latest iteration from Samsung and will not hesitate to recommend it to others.

132.review_text: Although I'm pleased with this phone overall, it's missing two features that I would REALLY like. First, the phone I had before would leave the music controls on the front screen, even when locked, if I was listening at the time it locked. I could still pause or skip without entering my PIN. Second, my son's phone, from a different manufacturer, has an FM tuner built in. Since my gym used FM for the audio on all of the TVs around the room, this would be a huge plus. Since this is supposed to be Samsung's flagship phone, I'd expect it to have a tuner (I'm sure the chip is capable). Video is beautiful, the phone seems fast, and everything seems to run smoothly. I'm not dissatisfied, but I am a little disappointed.
